2":"1330–1382","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1415":"1415","about 1382":"okolo 1382","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, Anglie","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1335–1395":"1335–1395","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1415":"1415","about 1382":"omkring 1382","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"nl":{"1335–1395":"1335–1395","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1415":"1415","about 1382":"circa 1382","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"en":{"1335–1395":"1335–1395","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1415":"1415","about 1382":"about 1382","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gregory","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: from a personal name that was popular throughout Christendom in the Middle Ages. The Greek original, <i>Grēgorios</i>, is a derivative of <i>grēgorein</i> ‘to be awake, to be watchful’. However, the Latin form, <i>Gregorius</i>, came to be associated by folk etymology with <i>grex</i>, <i>gregis</i> ‘flock, herd’, under the influence of the Christian image of the good shepherd. The Greek name was borne in the early Christian centuries by two fathers of the Orthodox Church, Saint Gregory Nazianzene (<i>c.</i> 325–390) and Saint Gregory of Nyssa (<i>c.</i> 331–395), and later by sixteen popes, starting with Gregory the Great (<i>c.</i> 540–604). It was also the name of 3rd- and 4th-century apostles of Armenia. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Gregorio  , German, Slovak, and Slovenian   Gregor  , Polish <b>Grzegorz</b>, Czech <b>Řehoř</b> (see   Rehor  ), and French   Gregoire  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Polish   Grzegorczyk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Goeres","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Markus.","North German (<b>Göres</b>): from a shortened form of the Latin personal name <i>Gregorius</i> (see   Gregory  , and compare   Gorr  )."]},{"name":"Goers","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Klaus, Otto.","North German (<b>Görs</b>): patronymic from <i>Goer</i>, a Low German form of the Latin personal name <i>Gregorius</i> (see   Gregory  )."]},{"name":"Gareis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Hans, Helmut.","German:","from a shortened form of the Latin personal name <i>Gregorius</i> (see   Gregory  )."]},{"name":"Gohr","meanings":["German: topographic name for someone living near a bog, from Middle Low German <i>gor</i> ‘quagmire, bog’, or a habitational name from any of the places called with this word, such as Gohr near Neuss.","East German (of Slavic origin): topographic name from Polish or other Slavic <i>gora</i> ‘mountain’ or from the root <i>gor-</i> (ultimately from Old Slavic <i>gorěti</i>) ‘to burn’ (denoting cleared forest), elements contained in various field names and placenames.","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Gór</b>: from a Lower Sorbian short form of the personal name <i>Gorisław</i> (from an Old Slavic name based on <i>gorěti</i> ‘to burn’) or <i>Grogor</i> (see   Gregory  )."]},{"name":"Gregorio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Mario, Fernando, Jose, Ramon, Juan, Roberto, Ana, Cesar, Francisco, Adolfo, Alberto.  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Salvatore, Carmine, Gennaro, Federico, Franco, Heriberto, Italo, Marco, Nicola.  Portuguese Henrique, Joaquim, Paulo.","Italian and Spanish; Portuguese (<b>Gregório</b>): from the personal name <i>Gregorio</i>, <i>Gregório</i> (see   Gregory  ). Compare   Di Gregorio  ."]},{"name":"Gergely","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Arpad, Bela, Attila, Dezso, Laszlo, Mihaly.","Hungarian: from the personal name <i>Gergely</i>, Hungarian form   Gregory  ."]},{"name":"Goris","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Julio, Alicia, Manuel, Maribel, Rafael, Agusto, Ana, Bernardina, Edmundo, Eladio.","Galician (<b>Gorís</b>): habitational name from Gorís in Pontevedra province, Galicia (Spain).","Dutch: patronymic from a vernacular of the personal name <i>Gregorius</i> (see   Gregory  )."]},{"name":"Gorr","meanings":["German:","from a short form of the personal name <i>Gregor</i>, Latin <i>Gregorius</i> (see   Gregory  ).","nickname from Middle High German <i>gorre</i> ‘bad horse’."]},{"name":"Gore","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece of land’ (Old English <i>gāra</i>, a derivative of <i>gār</i> ‘spear’, with reference to the triangular shape of a spearhead), a topographic name for someone living by a triangular field, or a habitational name from any of various places, for example Gore Court in Tunstall (Kent) and Gore Farm in Hannington (Wiltshire), named from this word.","French: from Old French <i>gore</i> ‘sow’ (a word of allegedly imitative origin, reflecting the grunting of the animal), applied as a metonymic occupational name for a swineherd or as an unflattering nickname.","French: probably also from a pet form of a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Grégoire</i> (see   Gregory  )."]},{"name":"Gori","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gino, Italo, Lido, Marco, Aldo, Angelo, Dino, Domenic, Fabiano, Livio, Luca, Secondo.","Italian (northern): patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Goro</i>, a shortened form of <i>Gregorio</i> (see   Gregory  ).","Swiss German: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Georg</i> (see   George  )."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Gregory was born in 1335, in Buckinghamshire, England. She had at least 2 sons with Thomas Ballard MP. She died in 1395, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1335–1395":"1335–1395","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1415":"1415","about 1382":"umbes 1382","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1335–1395":"1335–1395","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1415":"1415","about 1382":"noin 1382","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"1335–1395":"1335–1395","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1415":"1415","about 1382":"environ 1382","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, Angleterre","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Alice Gregory est née en 1335, à Buckinghamshire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec Thomas Ballard MP. Elle est décédée en 1395, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 60 ans."},"de":{"1335–1395":"1335–1395","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1415":"1415","about 1382":"um 1382","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buck